Using hint 2 provided, we may immediatley rewrite $f(t)$ as

\begin{align*}f(t)=-\int_2^{t^4} \sqrt{1+x^3}dx\end{align*}

We would like to use hint 1, but this only works if the upper limit of
integration is $t$, which in this case is not true. So define for the
time being

\begin{align*}g(u) = -\int_2^u \sqrt{1 + x^3}dx.\end{align*}

From hint 1, we see immediately that $g'(u) = -\sqrt{1 + u^3}$. We also
see that $f(t) = g(t^4)$. Using the chain rule we can then compute that

\begin{align*}f'(t) = g'(t^4) \frac{du}{dt} = -\sqrt{1 + (t^{4})^3}(4t^3) = -4t^3\sqrt{1 + t^{12}}.\end{align*}
